You heard it. Default considered harmful! tl;dr: Default has no defining or testable properties Default is not even guaranteed to be the same between runs Defaults are context-specific: One type does not always have one default Defaults are useful for transitive derivation, but context drift risks causing errors Your Default instance is dangerous if you cannot carelessly replace it with any other value Haskellers: Use the default* pattern instead Rustaceans: Use Default with care and respect Default in Rust and in Haskell
Rust's standard library has a Default trait that lets you provide a default value for any type: pub trait Default { fn default() -> Self; }
Returns the "default value" for a type. Default values are often some kind of initial value, identity value, or anything else…

